{{Location map|Japan Chiba|lat_deg=35|lat_min=47|lat_sec=8.1|lon_deg=140|lon_min=38|lon_sec=41.8|label=Sakurai Koyasu Shrine|position=bottom|width=220|mark=Japanese Map symbol (Shinto shrine).svg|marksize=12|caption={{Center|Location of Sakurai Koyasu Shrine}}}} '''Sakurai Koyasu Shrine''' (櫻井子安神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Asahi, Chiba|Asahi, Chiba]], [[Chiba Prefecture]], Japan.
== History == The shrine serves as an external shrine of the {{ill|Sayou Daijin|ja|左右大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sayou Daijin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 左右神社}}, overseen by the Kamishiro family. The enshrined deities are {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to コノハナノサクヤビメ}} (Konoha-no-sakuya-hime-no-mikoto), {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナギ}} (Izanagi-no-mikoto), and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナミ}} (Izanami-no-mikoto).
The exact date of its establishment is unknown, but it has been worshiped in this area since ancient times. Historically, the shrine has been revered as "Koyasu-sama of Sakurai" due to its blessings for good relationships, childbirth, and fertility. It was also known as "Sakurai Koyasu Daijin" in the past.
According to oral tradition, the shrine's red hemp cord (Koyasu-sama's red belt) symbolizes connections not only between couples but also between parents and children. It is believed that carrying the cord can fulfill wishes related to good relationships and fertility. Over time, it has also become a charm for health, academic success, and good fortune.
In addition, as some households in the region perform {{ill|Shinsōsai|ja|神葬祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsōsai|qq=}} (Shinto-style funerals), the shrine is respected as a guardian deity overseeing the entire life cycle—from birth, through rites of passage like [[:en:Shichi-Go-San|Shichi-Go-San]], to funerals.
== Enshrined Deities == * {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to コノハナノサクヤビメ}} * {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナギ}} * {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナミ}}
== Grounds == * Main Shrine * Shrine Office * Sacred Tree * Chōzusha (Ablution Pavilion) * Stone Monument
== Festivals == * January 1 - Saitan-sai (New Year's Festival) * September - Ujigami Festival * November - Annual Festival * 1st and 15th of every month - Tsukinami-sai (Monthly Festival)
== Access == From JR Sōbu Main Line, get off at Asahi Station, then walk 11 minutes from the Banzai Elementary School bus stop.
